In article <strnlghtCDsn2F.EBw@netcom.com> strnlght@netcom.com (David Sternlight) writes:
> That's one interpretation. Another, and the one the government is far more
> likely to make, is that since export is illegal, by seeking a foreign
> distributor Grady is attempting to circumvent U.S. law.

There is no such crime as ``attempting to circumvent U.S. law.'' If an 
action isn't explicitly prohibited, then it is allowed, even if it is a
``circumvention.''

> That's perhaps far
> more serious in the eyes of some prosecutors than an export or intent to
> export due to misunderstanding of the law, which ceases as soon as the law
> is explained to him (in this case to Austin by the State Dept.)

Ignorance of the law is no excuse, Sternlight.

---Dan
